----
== What can a Programming Language Do?

* Read/Write stdio and files
* Define and use variables
* Use loops and conditionals
* Define and use functions
* Math, string and collection operations
* Access environment variables
* Execute shell commands
* Load and use libraries
* Interact with databases and APIs
* Process data from various formats
* Access to standard libraries
* Provide an ecosystem of libraries

* YS does everything a programming language should!


----
== Using YS in YAML

$ vim file.yaml vars.yaml -O
$ ys -Y file.yaml


----
== Installing YS

$ curl -sL getys.org/ys | bash
$ which ys

$ git clone https://github.com/yaml/yamlscript
$ make -C yamlscript install-ys

* https://yamlscript.org/doc/install

$ ys --version
$ ys --help


----
== YS Baby Steps

$ vim baby1.ys
$ ys baby1.ys
$ ys -l baby1.ys
$ ys -l baby1.ys | jq .
$ ys -Y baby1.ys
$ ys -l baby1.ys | yq . | ys -Y
$ ys -J baby1.ys
$ ys --to=tsv baby1.ys

$ vim baby2.ys
$ ys -Y baby2.ys
$ FOO=1 ys -Y baby2.ys


----
== How to explain YS

* YS is hard to explain in a few words
* YS is a YAML loader library
  * It turns YAML files into code
  * It evaluates the code into a data structure
  * It returns the data as JSON
* YS is a programming language
  * Same as above but no return value
  * Results are side effects (files, stdout, etc)

* Input can be plain YAML
* Input can be all YS code
* Input can be a mix of YAML and YS code


